"""
mkt-context layer — Acts chapters 10–11
Output: data/commentary/mkt-context/acts.json
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-acts-10-11.py

Context layer focus: Roman military institutions (centurions, cohorts), Caesarea Maritima,
Jewish purity law and its social implications, the God-fearer category, the Cornelius
episode as a historical watershed, and the Antioch mission's sociological context.
Ch10:v1 and ch10:v28 already present; merge_comm skips them.
"""
import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    # INTENT: Merge new verse entries without overwriting already-present keys — safe to re-run.
    # CHANGE? If commentary JSON structure changes from {ch:{v:html}}, update this traversal.
    # VERIFY: Re-running the script should produce identical output (no duplicate or overwritten entries).
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

ACTS_CH10_11 = {
"10": {
"2": "<p>The category 'devout and God-fearing' (<em>eusebēs kai phoboumenos ton theon</em>) describes a well-attested class of Gentile synagogue-adherents in the first-century diaspora. Inscriptions from cities across Asia Minor and Aphrodisias specifically attest <em>theosebeis</em> ('God-fearers') as a distinct group separate from full proselytes: they attended synagogue, observed monotheism and basic Jewish ethics, and contributed to Jewish community welfare, but had not undergone circumcision. Josephus mentions God-fearing Gentiles in Antioch (<em>J.W.</em> 7.3.3). The 'Italian Regiment' to which Cornelius belongs identifies him as part of the Roman military aristocracy — a figure of substantial social prestige choosing Jewish religious affiliation.</p>",
"3": "<p>The 'ninth hour' (three in the afternoon) was one of the three traditional Jewish prayer-times (Ps 55:17 — 'evening, morning and noon I cry out'; m. Berakhot 4:1). This corresponds to the time of the afternoon <em>tamid</em> (daily sacrifice) in the temple. Josephus describes devout Jews maintaining prayer at this hour even in Rome (<em>Ant.</em> 14.10.12). Cornelius's observance of the ninth-hour prayer while stationed in Caesarea — far from the temple — is the God-fearer's diaspora practice of Jewish liturgical rhythms without direct temple participation. The angel's appearance at the prayer-hour is Luke's consistent pattern: divine communications come at moments of deliberate devotion.</p>",
"4": "<p>'Your prayers and gifts to the poor have come up as a memorial offering before God' — the language of ascending sacrifice applied to prayer and almsgiving echoes Tobit 12:12 ('I was sent to test you; at the same time, God sent me to heal you... When you prayed, I brought a reminder of your prayer before the Holy One'). The angel Raphael's similar function in Tobit — presenting prayers before God as a memorial — provides the conceptual framework: Cornelius's prayer and alms have been 'presented' to God as acceptable worship. Philo similarly describes prayer as equivalent to sacrifice in the life of the diaspora Jew (<em>Spec. Leg.</em> 1.272).</p>",
"5": "<p>Joppa (modern Jaffa, south of Tel Aviv) was one of Judaea's few Mediterranean ports, approximately 55 kilometers south of Caesarea Maritima. Simon the tanner's location 'by the sea' (v.6) is both a geographic marker and a sociological detail: tanners required water for their craft and typically lived at the margins of settlements because of the smell. Peter lodging with a tanner situates him already on the social boundary — the guest of a ritually marginalized craftsman — before the vision pushes him further across the purity lines.</p>",
"6": "<p>The tanner's profession (<em>burseus</em> — leather worker) placed him in a category of ritual marginality in rabbinic law: constant contact with animal carcasses made sustained Levitical purity extremely difficult. The Mishnah (m. Ketubot 7:10) listed the tanner's trade as grounds for divorce if a wife objected to marrying into the profession; tanners were typically required to live 50 cubits from the edge of town (m. Baba Batra 2:9). Peter's willingness to lodge with Simon the tanner thus already represents a relaxed attitude toward purity-boundary-maintaining — contextualizing the rooftop vision's more radical demand.</p>",
"7": "<p>'A devout soldier who was one of his attendants' (<em>stratiōtēn eusebē tōn proskarterountōn autō</em>) — Cornelius's household includes a soldier described with the same <em>eusebēs</em> (devout) as Cornelius himself. The Greek term <em>proskarterountōn</em> (those who attend/serve continuously) describes personal attendants or bodyguards. A centurion's household in Roman military culture included personal servants, freedmen, and soldiers assigned to his administrative service. The devout soldier represents the God-fearing influence extending through Cornelius's household structure.</p>",
"8": "<p>Cornelius's sending of three men (two servants + one soldier) on a 55-kilometer journey to Joppa mirrors the precise number the Spirit reports to Peter ('three men are looking for you,' v.19). The two-way divine coordination — angel to Cornelius in Caesarea, Spirit to Peter in Joppa — is Luke's characteristic demonstration of divine orchestration operating simultaneously on two separated individuals. The journey of approximately 55 km on Roman roads would take about two days (consistent with 'the following day' in v.9 and 'the next day' in v.23).</p>",
"9": "<p>Rooftop prayer was a recognized practice in Judaism; the flat roofs of Palestinian houses provided both privacy and the elevated orientation toward heaven associated with prayer. Rooftops appear throughout Jewish literature as spaces for prayer, meditation, and divine encounter: Daniel 6:10 (Daniel prays toward Jerusalem from his window); Judith 8:5 (she pitched a tent on her roof for fasting); Tobit 3:11 (Tobias went to the roof to pray). Peter's midday (sixth hour) prayer may represent a personal devotional practice beyond the three standard prayer times.</p>",
"10": "<p>The 'trance' (<em>ekstasis</em> — literally 'standing outside oneself') is the technical Greek term for the visionary state in which ordinary consciousness is suspended and divine perception substituted. The LXX uses <em>ekstasis</em> for the deep sleep that fell on Adam during the creation of Eve (Gen 2:21) and Abraham's vision (Gen 15:12). Jewish apocalyptic literature uses the term for the prophetic state of reception (1 En. 71:11; 4 Ezra 10:30-57). Luke uses it for Peter's vision here and Paul's temple vision (Acts 22:17). The combination of hunger-induced physical receptivity and the onset of <em>ekstasis</em> is a recognized pattern in ancient descriptions of visionary experience.</p>",
"11": "<p>'Heaven opened' (<em>ouranon aneōgmenon</em>) is the standard theophany-formula in Jewish and Christian visionary literature: Ezekiel's chariot-vision begins 'the heavens were opened' (Ezek 1:1 LXX); the Synoptics use it for Jesus's baptism (Mark 1:10); Revelation 19:11 uses it for the final vision. The 'sheet' (<em>othonē</em> — a linen cloth, sail-canvas) let down by four corners images both a container for the animal contents and a spatial metaphor for the four corners of the earth (Isa 11:12 — God gathering Israel 'from the four corners of the earth').</p>",
"12": "<p>The three categories of animals (four-footed creatures, reptiles, and birds) follow the creation-taxonomy of Genesis 1:24-25 and Leviticus 11's clean/unclean divisions. The Levitical food laws (Lev 11; Deut 14:3-21) governed which animals could be eaten by Israel, functioning as a daily marker of covenant distinctiveness. The sheet contained <em>panta ta tetrapoda</em> (all the four-footed animals) — the 'all' (<em>panta</em>) is the key: both clean and unclean together, without distinction. The vision's content is not primarily about food but about the category-system of clean/unclean that the food laws instantiated.</p>",
"13": "<p>The divine command 'Get up, Peter. Kill and eat' (<em>anastas thuson kai phage</em>) represents the direct overriding of Levitical food law by divine command. The imperative <em>anasta</em> (rise!) is the same command-form used throughout Luke-Acts for healings and resurrection-announcements. The combination <em>thuson kai phage</em> (kill and eat — using <em>thyō</em>, the sacrificial-slaughter verb) presents the meal as a quasi-sacrificial act — the food prepared for eating is to be treated as an offering, authorized directly by God rather than by Levitical regulation.</p>",
"14": "<p>Peter's refusal — 'I have never eaten anything impure or unclean' (<em>oudepote ephagon pan koinon kai akatharton</em>) — uses the two key technical terms of Jewish dietary law: <em>koinos</em> (common, i.e., ritually non-sacred and therefore defiling) and <em>akathartos</em> (unclean). The rabbinic tradition preserved in m. Hullin discusses in detail which animal parts and preparation methods result in <em>tum'ah</em> (impurity). Peter's claim of lifelong dietary purity is plausible given his Galilean Jewish formation; it also establishes the magnitude of the vision's demand — not a minor adjustment but a complete reversal of lifelong practice.</p>",
"15": "<p>'Do not call anything impure that God has made clean' — the theological claim is that God's creative authority supersedes the Levitical categorization system. The same reasoning appears in Mark 7:19 ('Thus he declared all foods clean') as an editorial comment on Jesus's teaching, and in Paul's argument in Romans 14:14 ('Nothing is unclean in itself; but it is unclean for anyone who thinks it is unclean') and 1 Corinthians 10:25-26 (citing Ps 24:1 — 'the earth is the Lord's and everything in it'). The common theological ground: God's ownership of creation overrides any secondary categorization derived from covenant-law regulations.</p>",
"16": "<p>The triple repetition of the vision follows the biblical and rabbinic convention that a divine communication occurring three times establishes certainty and eliminates the possibility of misinterpretation. Joseph's dreams were interpreted as certain because of their repetition (Gen 41:32 — 'the reason the dream was given to Pharaoh twice is that the matter has been firmly decided by God'). The three repetitions of Peter's vision follow this convention: the triple command removes any ambiguity about the divine will. The sheet's immediate withdrawal (<em>anelēmphthē</em>) before Peter has resolved the vision's interpretation is deliberate — he must hold the unresolved meaning in mind as the Cornelius messengers arrive.</p>",
"17": "<p>The divine timing of the Cornelius messengers' arrival at the gate while Peter is still perplexed about the vision's meaning is Luke's characteristic demonstration of divine simultaneity: two events in two cities, coordinated by one divine director. The 'gate' (<em>pylōna</em>) of Simon the tanner's house is the entrance-passage of a courtyard house — the standard Palestinian domestic architecture where a gatehouse or gate-room (pylōn) provided access from the street to the inner courtyard. The Cornelius messengers standing at the gate while Peter is on the roof represents the physical distance between the purity-boundary (house interior) and the outside world.</p>",
"18": "<p>The messengers' inquiry about 'Simon who is known as Peter' (<em>Simōna ton epikaloumenon Petron</em>) uses the double-name designation that Luke consistently employs throughout Acts for the apostle. The Aramaic Simon (the name Jesus gave; Matt 16:17-18) and the Greek Peter (translation of Kepha/Cephas — rock) together signal the bilingual Jewish-Hellenistic context: Peter is identifiable by either name, reflecting his movement between Aramaic-speaking Palestinian Jewish contexts and Greek-speaking diaspora contexts.</p>",
"19": "<p>The Spirit's direct address to Peter ('Simon, three men are looking for you') provides the interpretive bridge between the food-vision and the arriving Gentile delegation. The Spirit (<em>pneuma</em>) who speaks directly and audibly to Peter is the same Spirit who will fall on Cornelius's household (v.44-45), connecting the two events in a single pneumatological arc. The precision of 'three men' confirms that the Spirit has real-time knowledge of the situation at the gate — the divine orchestration operates with exact detail, not general providence.</p>",
"20": "<p>'Do not hesitate to go with them, for I have sent them' (<em>mēden diakrinomenos hoti egō apestalka autous</em>) — the Spirit's claim that Cornelius's Gentile messengers are the Spirit's own ambassadors is the theological watershed: the pagan centurion's servants are here declared to be divinely commissioned. <em>Apostellō</em> (to send, the verb from which 'apostle' derives) — the Spirit uses apostolic language for Cornelius's household servants. The Spirit's claim of ownership over the Gentile messengers will be the basis for Peter's defense in 11:12 ('the Spirit told me to go with them').</p>",
"21": "<p>Peter's hospitality to the Gentile messengers (v.23 — 'Peter invited the men into the house to be his guests') is itself a boundary-crossing act: Jewish purity rules discouraged hosting Gentiles in Jewish homes. The Mishnah (m. Oholot 18:7) declares that 'the dwellings of Gentiles are unclean.' Peter's invitation of the three Gentiles into Simon the tanner's house — already a ritually marginal location — represents the first step of the practical boundary-crossing that the vision authorized.</p>",
"22": "<p>'Respected by all the Jewish nation' (<em>martyroumenon hypo holou tou ethnous tōn Ioudaiōn</em>) — Cornelius's reputation with the Jewish community in Caesarea is a significant social detail. A Roman centurion who was a God-fearer and philanthropist toward the Jewish community would have been known and respected across that community. Josephus mentions similar Gentile benefactors of Jewish communities in diaspora cities (<em>J.W.</em> 7.3.3). The messengers' description of Cornelius positions him as the most favorably situated possible Gentile recipient of the gospel — not a hostile Roman but a respected friend of Israel.</p>",
"23": "<p>'Some of the believers from Joppa went along' (v.23 — 'six brothers' according to 11:12) — the witnesses traveling with Peter establish the Deuteronomic two-or-three-witnesses requirement for legally valid testimony (Deut 19:15). Their presence at Cornelius's house makes them the corroborating witnesses who will testify to the Jerusalem church in 11:12 ('these six brothers also accompanied me'). Luke consistently documents the witness-structures that give apostolic events their evidential standing before the wider community.</p>",
"24": "<p>Caesarea Maritima was Herod the Great's showpiece city, built between 22-10 BCE: a completely artificial deep-water harbor (the largest in the ancient Mediterranean), a Roman grid city plan, temples, an amphitheater, a hippodrome, and an aqueduct. As Rome's administrative capital of Judaea, Caesarea housed the Roman prefect/procurator's residence and the garrison of Roman troops. Cornelius's house in Caesarea — the Roman city par excellence — means that the first Gentile conversion takes place not in Jerusalem's Jewish heartland but in Rome's representative presence in Palestine.</p>",
"25": "<p>Cornelius's falling at Peter's feet (<em>pesōn epi tous podas proskunēsen</em>) is the obeisance-gesture associated with divine or royal figures. <em>Proskuneō</em> encompasses the range from prostration before a god to bowing before a king to kneeling before a superior. In the Roman military context, soldiers performed structured gestures of respect before their superiors; Cornelius's prostration before Peter represents the highest-intensity respect gesture available, appropriate for someone he has received divine instruction to contact. The same gesture appears at Revelation 19:10 and 22:8 (John falls before the angel) with the same correction: 'stand up.'</p>",
"26": "<p>Peter's refusal of worship ('Stand up, I am only a man myself,' <em>kai egō autos anthrōpos eimi</em>) follows the consistent apostolic pattern of deflecting divine honors in Acts (14:14-15 — Paul and Barnabas tear their clothes at Lystra). The same refusal appears in the Greek-speaking world's descriptions of the proper response to divine attribution: Plutarch describes how virtuous rulers refused divine honors as a matter of philosophical propriety. The contrast with Herod Agrippa (12:21-23 — who accepts divine acclamation and is struck dead) will highlight the apostolic behavior as the correct posture before God-attributed glory.</p>",
"27": "<p>The 'large gathering of people' (<em>pollous synelēluthotas</em>) that Cornelius had assembled represents the household-as-social-network: relatives (<em>syngeneis</em>) and close friends (<em>ananagkaioi philoi</em> — those bound by close obligation). The gathering of an extended household for a significant occasion was standard practice in Greco-Roman social life; the <em>patron-client</em> relationship structure meant that a centurion's household encompassed a broad social network. Cornelius's assembled household becomes the first Gentile community baptized as a group — the household as mission-unit rather than the individual as conversion-unit.</p>",
"29": "<p>'When I was sent for, I came without raising any objection' (<em>anadikritōs</em> — without discriminating/raising objections) — the word <em>anadiakritōs</em> echoes the Spirit's command not to 'discriminate/hesitate' (<em>mēden diakrinomenos</em>, v.20). Peter's report to Cornelius is the first step of the double-narrative structure Luke employs throughout the Cornelius episode: everything is reported twice (vision → report to Cornelius; Cornelius's vision → report to Peter; Peter's visit → report to Jerusalem). The double-narration serves Luke's historiographical purpose of providing multiple-witness confirmation for the theologically decisive event.</p>",
"30": "<p>'Three days ago I was in my house praying at three in the afternoon' — Cornelius's precise temporal reconstruction confirms the divine synchronization: the same ninth hour that was his regular prayer time (v.3) was the hour of the angelic visit. The 'man in shining clothes' (<em>anēr en esthēti lampra</em>) is described differently here (shining clothes) than in v.3 (where Luke simply narrates 'an angel'): the first-person report uses the phenomenological description (what Cornelius saw), while Luke's third-person narration uses the interpretive description (what it was). The same two-perspective technique appears in Acts 9 (Luke narrates Paul's Damascus encounter; Paul reports it in 22:6-16; 26:12-18).</p>",
"31": "<p>'God has heard your prayer and remembered your gifts to the poor' — the angel's message to Cornelius deploys two OT covenant-response formulas: God 'hearing' prayer (<em>eisēkousthē sou hē proseuchē</em>) echoes the Psalms' frequent affirmation of God's attentiveness to the righteous (Ps 4:3; 17:6; 34:15-17); God 'remembering' (<em>emnēsthēsan</em>) is the covenant-memory vocabulary of Gen 8:1 (God remembered Noah), Gen 19:29 (God remembered Abraham), Gen 30:22 (God remembered Rachel). The angel frames Cornelius's Gentile prayer and almsgiving within the covenant-response pattern that belongs to Israel.</p>",
"32": "<p>The repeated mention of Simon the tanner 'who lives by the sea' (<em>para thalassan</em>) — first in the angel's message (v.6), now in Cornelius's report — is Luke's verification technique: the precision of the address (name, profession, location) is repeated exactly across the two narrative tellings, confirming the reliability of the communication. Joppa's location on the Mediterranean coast and the tanner's house 'by the sea' are geographically consistent: tanneries required constant water access.</p>",
"33": "<p>'We are all here in the presence of God to listen to everything the Lord has commanded you to tell us' — Cornelius's framing of the assembled household as a divine assembly (<em>enōpion tou theou</em> — before God) positions the Gentile gathering as a theophanic occasion. The language recalls the Sinai assembly ('Israel stood before God,' Exod 19:17) and the synagogue service as a gathering before the divine presence. Cornelius's theological characterization of his own household gathering is more sophisticated than might be expected from a pagan soldier — the God-fearer's extended engagement with Jewish theological vocabulary is evident.</p>",
"34": "<p>The phrase 'God does not show favoritism' (<em>prosōpolēmptēs</em> — one who accepts/shows the face/person) is a NT hapax (only here in the NT as a noun; the related verb <em>prosōpolēmpteō</em> appears in Jas 2:9). The compound represents the Hebrew <em>nāśā' pānîm</em> ('to lift the face/show favor'), a phrase used throughout the OT for showing partiality in judgment (Lev 19:15; Deut 1:17; 16:19). Peter's theological insight — that what he had always believed about God's impartial justice in individual moral judgment now extends to ethnic inclusion in the covenant community — is the watershed theological realization of the chapter.</p>",
"35": "<p>'Everyone who fears him and does what is right is acceptable to him' — the principle of divine acceptance based on reverential fear and right-action rather than ethnic membership was not wholly new in Jewish tradition. The OT regularly affirmed that God's concern extended to all nations (Gen 12:3; Amos 9:7 — 'Are not you Israelites the same to me as the Cushites?'). Philo argued for God's universal justice. The Noahide commandments (rabbinic tradition: b. Sanhedrin 56a-60a) defined the obligations incumbent on all humanity before God. Peter's insight builds on existing Jewish universalism but extends it to include Gentiles in the messianic community without requiring circumcision.</p>",
"36": "<p>'The message God sent to the people of Israel, announcing the good news of peace through Jesus Christ' — Peter's brief sermon rehearsal (vv.36-43) for Cornelius's household follows the pattern of Paul's sermon in Acts 13:23-41 and the summary of early preaching preserved in 1 Corinthians 15:3-5. Both include: the John-Baptist context, the Galilean ministry, the Jerusalem death, the resurrection, the appearances, and the witness-claim. This consistent preaching structure (the <em>kerygma</em>) across multiple Acts speeches suggests Luke is working with a preserved summary of early Christian proclamation.</p>",
"37": "<p>'You know what has happened throughout the province of Judea, beginning in Galilee' — Cornelius's presumed knowledge of the Jesus-movement is plausible: as a centurion in Caesarea, he would have access to official reports, local gossip, and the accounts of Jewish informants about the religious teacher who had caused significant political disturbance in Jerusalem three to five years before. Josephus's reference to Jesus (<em>Ant.</em> 18.3.3 — the <em>Testimonium Flavianum</em>, even in its debated form) suggests that the movement was regionally known. Peter's appeal to what Cornelius 'knows' (<em>hymeis oidate</em>) grounds the proclamation in shared background knowledge.</p>",
"38": "<p>'God anointed Jesus of Nazareth with the Holy Spirit and power, and how he went around doing good and healing all who were under the power of the devil' — the summary of Jesus's ministry in terms of anointing (<em>echrisen</em> — from which <em>Christos</em>/Christ derives), Holy Spirit, power (<em>dynamis</em>), benefaction (<em>euergetōn</em> — the civic benefactor vocabulary), and healing against demonic opposition provides the theological framework in which the Jesus-story would be comprehensible to a Roman military audience: a divinely commissioned benefactor empowered by the divine spirit who liberated people from a hostile supernatural power.</p>",
"39": "<p>'We are witnesses of everything he did in the country of the Jews and in Jerusalem. They killed him by hanging him on a cross' (<em>kremesantes epi xylou</em> — hanging on a tree) — the apostolic witness-claim ('we are witnesses') is the foundation of the proclamation: the apostles are not transmitting doctrine but reporting events they personally observed. The crucifixion's public, state-sponsored nature meant it was verifiable by anyone who had been in Jerusalem during Passover — Cornelius as a Roman officer might have had access to Roman records of a public execution under Pontius Pilate.</p>",
"40": "<p>'God raised him from the dead on the third day and caused him to be seen' (<em>edōken auton emphanē genesthai</em> — allowed/caused him to become visible/manifest) — the third-day formula is among the earliest fixed elements of Christian proclamation (1 Cor 15:4 — 'raised on the third day according to the Scriptures'). The passive formulation ('caused him to be seen') emphasizes that the resurrection appearances were divinely controlled: God chose the witnesses, God selected the occasions. The passive voice consistently ascribes the resurrection to divine action rather than natural events.</p>",
"41": "<p>'Not to all the people, but to witnesses whom God had already chosen — by us who ate and drank with him after he rose from the dead' — the selectivity of the resurrection appearances (not to all Jerusalem but to specific pre-chosen witnesses) distinguishes the resurrection from hallucination or mass suggestion: the appearances were targeted and controlled by divine selection. The 'ate and drank with him' (<em>sunepiomen kai synephagomen autō</em>) formula is the bodily-resurrection apologetic: spiritual visions do not eat and drink; the resurrection appearances involved shared meals (Luke 24:41-43; John 21:9-13).</p>",
"42": "<p>'He commanded us to preach to the people and to testify that he is the one whom God appointed as judge of the living and the dead' — the title 'judge of the living and the dead' (<em>kritēs zōntōn kai nekrōn</em>) is the earliest attested formula for Jesus's judicial role at the final judgment (2 Tim 4:1; 1 Pet 4:5). In the Roman legal context (Cornelius's world), the appointment of a specific judicial authority (<em>horistheis hypo tou theou</em> — appointed/designated by God) as the definitive court of appeal would be comprehensible. The resurrection (v.40) is the basis for this judicial appointment: the one who conquered death has authority to preside over all life and death.</p>",
"43": "<p>'All the prophets testify about him that everyone who believes in him receives forgiveness of sins through his name' — Peter's appeal to 'all the prophets' (<em>pantes hoi prophētai</em>) corresponds to the 'Moses and all the Prophets' of the Emmaus road exposition (Luke 24:27) — the claim that the entire prophetic corpus witnesses to Jesus. Specific prophets cited in Acts include: Joel (2:17-21), Amos (15:16-17), Isaiah (7:17-52; 8:32-33; 28:25-27), and the Psalms (2:25-28; 4:25-26). The universal-scope 'everyone who believes' (<em>panta ton pisteuonta</em>) will be immediately tested and demonstrated by the Spirit's falling on the uncircumcised Gentile hearers before Peter finishes speaking.</p>",
"44": "<p>The Spirit's interruption of Peter's sermon before its conclusion — 'while Peter was still speaking these words' (<em>eti lalountos tou Petrou ta rhēmata tauta</em>) — is both dramatic and theologically decisive: the Spirit does not wait for formal completion of the gospel presentation, the invitation, the prayer, or the response. The Spirit falls on faith-generated receptivity, not on a completed ritual sequence. This 'anti-ritual' aspect of the Cornelius Pentecost will be Peter's strongest argument to the Jerusalem church (11:15 — 'as I began to speak, the Holy Spirit came on them as he had come on us at the beginning').</p>",
"45": "<p>'The circumcised believers who had come with Peter were astonished' (<em>exestēsan</em> — were beside themselves, thoroughly amazed) — the word <em>existēmi</em> (to stand outside oneself) is related to <em>ekstasis</em> (trance, v.10) — the same family of words for being outside ordinary consciousness. The Jewish Christian witnesses to Cornelius's Pentecost are as 'beside themselves' with astonishment as Peter was in his trance — the divine surprise operates equally on both recipient and observer. 'Even on Gentiles' (<em>kai epi ta ethnē</em>) — the <em>kai</em> (even, also) is the shock-marker: the Pentecost gift has crossed the boundary that Jewish theology had maintained between Israel and the nations.</p>",
"46": "<p>'They heard them speaking in tongues and praising God' — the twin signs of Gentile Spirit-reception (glossolalia + praise) match exactly the Acts 2 Pentecost signs (2:4 — spoke in tongues; 2:11 — declaring the wonders of God in our own languages). Luke's consistent deployment of the Pentecost sign-pattern at each geographic expansion of the Spirit's reach (Jerusalem, Samaria/ch.8, Caesarea, Ephesus/ch.19) creates a narrative theology of Spirit-geography: the same Spirit who inaugurated the Jewish-Christian community at Pentecost is progressively claiming new territory without modification or diminution.</p>",
"47": "<p>'Surely no one can stand in the way of their being baptised with water?' (<em>mēti to hydōr kōlysai dynatai tis</em>) — the baptism-prevention question (<em>kōlyō</em> — to prevent, hinder, forbid) appears again at 8:36 ('what prevents me from being baptized?') and in early Christian baptismal liturgy (Didache 7; Justin Martyr, <em>Apology</em> 1.61). The rhetorical question form — 'can anyone prevent?' — is the standard formula for baptismal inclusion: the burden of proof rests on preventing, not on baptizing. The Spirit's prior gift makes water-baptism the formal seal of what has already occurred inwardly.</p>",
"48": "<p>'Baptised in the name of Jesus Christ' (<em>en tō onomati Iēsou Christou</em>) — the single-name baptismal formula in Acts (2:38; 8:16; 10:48; 19:5) has been extensively debated relative to Matthew 28:19's trinitarian formula. The two formulas are not contradictory: baptism 'in Jesus's name' identifies the authority and community into which one is baptized; the trinitarian formula specifies the divine persons who are invoked. Early Christian practice likely varied, with Acts reflecting the primitive Aramaic formula and Matthew the developed Greek liturgical form. 'They asked Peter to stay with them for a few days' — the post-baptismal table-fellowship (implied in the extended stay) sealed the social integration that the Spirit and water had enacted.</p>"
},
"11": {
"1": "<p>'The apostles and the believers throughout Judea heard that the Gentiles had also received the word of God' — news traveled through the early church via the same networks of travel and communication that served the Roman world: itinerant merchants, imperial post routes, and the movement of pilgrims and travelers between cities. The speed with which the Jerusalem community heard about the Caesarea event reflects both the relatively compact size of the early church and the importance attached to any significant theological development. The reaction ('the circumcised believers took issue with him,' v.2) demonstrates that the Cornelius event was immediately recognized as a boundary-crossing requiring communal adjudication.</p>",
"2": "<p>'The circumcised believers' (<em>hoi ek peritomēs</em> — those from/of the circumcision) is the technical designation for Jewish Christians who maintained circumcision as a necessary covenant marker. The same group appears in Galatians 2:12 ('certain men from James... belonged to the circumcision group') and Titus 1:10 ('especially those of the circumcision group'). Their challenge to Peter represents a theological controversy that will persist in the church through Paul's Galatian and Roman letters: whether circumcision remained a requirement for full covenant membership in the messianic community.</p>",
"3": "<p>'You went into the house of uncircumcised men and ate with them' (<em>eisēlthen pros andras akrobystian echontas kai synephages autois</em>) — the charge specifically focuses on table-fellowship (<em>synephages</em> — you ate together with them) rather than baptism. Entering a Gentile's house incurred ritual impurity according to rabbinic tradition (m. Oholot 18:7 — Gentile dwellings are unclean); sharing a meal with Gentiles violated the purity-maintenance that regular prayer and temple attendance required. The Jerusalem criticism reflects the practical piety concerns of Torah-observant Jewish believers, not merely institutional Pharisaism.</p>",
"4": "<p>'Starting from the beginning, Peter explained everything to them in order' (<em>kathexēs exetitheto autois</em>) — <em>kathexēs</em> is Luke's characteristic word for orderly sequential narration (Luke 1:3; Acts 3:24; 18:23). Peter's orderly defense before the Jerusalem believers follows the standard form of the Hellenistic defense speech (<em>apologia</em>): chronological presentation of events in the order they occurred, with each element leading logically to the conclusion. Luke's double narration of the Cornelius episode (first in his own voice, 10:1-48; then in Peter's, 11:4-17) is his authentication technique: the story that can be told consistently from two perspectives is reliable.</p>",
"5": "<p>'I was in the city of Joppa praying, and in a trance I saw a vision' — Peter's first-person account begins from his subjective experience rather than from Cornelius's story (which Luke's narration in ch.10 had begun with). The personal-experience starting point is the rhetorical choice of someone offering testimony: begin from what you yourself saw and heard, not from the external event. The self-description as in a 'trance' (<em>ekstasei</em>) validates the visionary state's authenticity — Peter is not reporting a dream or a wishful interpretation but an <em>ekstasis</em>, the recognized category of genuine prophetic revelation.</p>",
"6": "<p>The expansion of the animal list in Peter's report ('four-footed animals of the earth, wild beasts, reptiles, and birds') compared to the original account (10:12 — no 'wild beasts') may reflect either a different tradition, memory expansion in the retelling, or deliberate rhetorical emphasis: by adding 'wild beasts' (<em>thēria</em> — the most obviously 'unclean' category), Peter makes the vision's inclusiveness even more comprehensive in the retelling before the Jerusalem critics. Retelling with slightly expanded detail is a recognized feature of eyewitness accounts in both ancient and modern psychology of memory.</p>",
"7": "<p>'Kill and eat' — Peter's verbatim repetition of the divine command in testimony is the standard form of divine-command reporting in both OT (Moses reporting God's words to Israel; prophets quoting the divine voice) and Greco-Roman legal contexts (witnesses repeated exact words, not paraphrases). The verbatim divine command, reproduced twice in the narrative (10:13; 11:7), functions as the unchanging divine word that must be obeyed — its repetition across the double narration confirms that the command was specific, clear, and binding.</p>",
"8": "<p>Peter's reformulation of his refusal in the testimony ('Nothing impure or unclean has ever entered my mouth') uses <em>stoma</em> (mouth) instead of the original <em>ephagon</em> (I ate) — an intensification: the mouth as the entry-point emphasizes the bodily contact with impurity that the refusal was preventing. The switch from 'I have never eaten' (direct, first-person past act) to 'nothing has ever entered my mouth' (categorical, body-centered claim) reflects either normal variation in oral retelling or a deliberate rhetorical choice to make the refusal's totality vivid for the Jerusalem audience who will immediately understand the bodily-purity implications.</p>",
"9": "<p>'The voice spoke from heaven a second time' — the condensation of the three repetitions (10:15-16) to 'a second time' in the retelling reflects the rhetorical compression of summary: Peter gives the essential content rather than exhaustive detail. The <em>phōnē ek tou ouranou</em> (voice from heaven) is the <em>bath qol</em> ('daughter of a voice' — the rabbinic term for divine communication through an auditory phenomenon short of direct prophecy; cf. Matt 3:17; John 12:28; Acts 9:4). The divine voice from heaven carries the authentication weight of direct revelation.</p>",
"10": "<p>The triple repetition and withdrawal to heaven, condensed to 'this happened three times and then it was all pulled back up into heaven' (<em>kai anespasthē palin hapanta eis ton ouranon</em>), receives its confirmation number. Three repetitions of a divine communication in Jewish tradition establish the communication's certainty and binding character (Jonah 1:17 — three days in the fish; the three visions of the book of Daniel; the threefold call to Samuel, 1 Sam 3:8-10). The immediate withdrawal terminates the vision before interpretation, requiring the recipient to carry the unresolved meaning into encounter with the events that will explain it.</p>",
"11": "<p>'Right then three men who had been sent to me from Caesarea stopped at the house where I was staying' (<em>kai idou exautēs treis andres epestēsan epi tēn oikian</em>) — <em>kai idou</em> (and behold!) is Luke's particle of providential coincidence: the unexpected event that reveals divine coordination behind the surface of simultaneity. Peter's use of <em>exautēs</em> (immediately, right then) emphasizes the precision of the timing: not 'later that day' but at the exact moment the vision's perplexity was still unresolved. The Cornelius messengers' arrival as the divine explanation of the unresolved vision is the interpretive key Peter offers to the Jerusalem critics.</p>",
"12": "<p>'These six brothers also went with me' — Peter's identification of the six witnesses by their role as accompanying witnesses ('six brothers') rather than by name provides the legal framework for his testimony: Deuteronomy 19:15's requirement of two or three witnesses is exceeded. The six Jewish-Christian witnesses to the Cornelius event constitute a super-majority witness-testimony that can be cross-examined by the Jerusalem church. Luke consistently documents the witness-structures that give apostolic events their legal standing (1:21-22; 2:32; 3:15; 5:32; 10:39-41).</p>",
"13": "<p>The chain of reporting that Peter rehearses — angel to Cornelius → Cornelius to Peter's messengers → messengers to Peter → Peter to Jerusalem — constitutes a multi-link chain of testimony. Each link in the chain is a separate witness to the divine initiation of the event. Luke's interest in multiple-corroborated testimony reflects both his historiographical method (Luke 1:1-4 — 'handed down to us by those who from the first were eyewitnesses') and the early church's theological need to demonstrate that the inclusion of Gentiles was not a human innovation but a divinely initiated event with multiple independent witnesses.</p>",
"14": "<p>'He will bring you a message through which you and all your household will be saved' (<em>rhēmata di' hōn sōthēsē su kai pas ho oikos sou</em>) — the household-salvation scope is the distinctive unit of Cornelius's conversion: not merely Cornelius as an individual but his entire household. This matches the pattern throughout Acts: Lydia and her household (16:15), the Philippian jailer and his household (16:34), Crispus and his household (18:8). The household as the primary social unit of ancient Mediterranean life becomes the primary unit of the gospel's reception — the conversion of a household-head brought his entire social and domestic network into the community.</p>",
"15": "<p>'As I began to speak, the Holy Spirit came on them as he had come on us at the beginning' (<em>en archē</em> — at the beginning) — Peter's reference to 'the beginning' situates the Cornelius Pentecost in relation to the Jerusalem Pentecost as the normative event. The phrase <em>en archē</em> echoes John 1:1 ('In the beginning was the Word') and Genesis 1:1 ('In the beginning God created') — both primordial starting points. The Cornelius event is measured against the foundational Pentecost as its extension: the same Spirit, the same pattern, the same beginning repeated in a new location with a new people.</p>",
"16": "<p>'John baptized with water, but you will be baptized with the Holy Spirit' (<em>Iōannēs men ebaptisen hydati, hymeis de baptisthēsesthe en pneumati hagiō</em>) — the Lord's prophetic word recalled by Peter is from Acts 1:5 (cf. Luke 3:16; Matt 3:11; Mark 1:8). The contrast water/Spirit is the Baptist's own formulation: his preparatory water-baptism pointed forward to the messianic Spirit-baptism. Peter's recollection at this moment — 'I remembered the Lord's words' (<em>emnēsthēn de tou rhēmatos Kyriou</em>) — is the interpretive breakthrough: the Cornelius event is the fulfillment of a specific prophetic word that defines what Spirit-baptism means and who receives it.</p>",
"17": "<p>'So if God gave them the same gift he gave us when we believed in the Lord Jesus Christ, who was I to think that I could oppose God?' — the rhetorical question (<em>egō tis ēmēn dynatos kōlysai ton theon</em> — who was I to be able to hinder God?) positions Peter as the potential obstacle: the human barrier that could have frustrated divine intention. The same <em>kōlyō</em> (to hinder, prevent) that Peter had used rhetorically at the baptism ('can anyone hinder the water?', 10:47) is now applied to the hypothetical of hindering God. The theological conclusion is irresistible: if God initiated, God authenticated, and God gave the same gift — to resist would be <em>theomachein</em> (fighting against God).</p>",
"18": "<p>'So then, even to Gentiles God has granted repentance that leads to life' (<em>ara kai tois ethnesin ho theos tēn metanoian eis zōēn edōken</em>) — the Jerusalem church's conclusion is the first formal ecclesial recognition of Gentile inclusion without circumcision. <em>Metanoia</em> (repentance) as God's gift (<em>edōken</em> — has given) rather than human achievement reflects the consistent Acts theology: even the turning-toward-God is God's grant, not human initiation (5:31 — 'God exalted him... to give repentance and forgiveness of sins to Israel'). The extension of the same gift to Gentiles completes the universalization of what was first given to Israel.</p>",
"19": "<p>'Those who had been scattered by the persecution that broke out when Stephen was killed' — the connection back to Stephen's death (7:54-8:3) creates a narrative arc: the persecution that scattered the Jerusalem community (8:1 — 'they were all scattered throughout Judea and Samaria') becomes the mechanism of the mission's geographic expansion. Phoenicia (the Lebanese coast), Cyprus (Barnabas's homeland, 4:36), and Antioch represent the three primary destinations of the Stephen-scattered believers — all significant diaspora centers with established Jewish communities and synagogues that served as the initial mission contexts.</p>",
"20": "<p>'Men from Cyprus and Cyrene went to Antioch and began to speak to Greeks also' (<em>Hellēnas</em> — Greeks, not <em>Hellēnistai</em>/Greek-speaking Jews) — the Antioch breakthrough differs from Cornelius in its agents (unnamed Cypriot and Cyrenian missionaries, not apostles) and its context (an urban Gentile population in the empire's third-largest city, not a God-fearing Roman centurion). Antioch (Syrian Antioch, modern Antakya/Antiochia on the Orontes) was a city of approximately half a million people, with a large and established Jewish community. The missionaries' transition from preaching to Hellenist Jews to preaching to ethnic Greeks (<em>Hellēnas</em>) is the sociological watershed for Gentile-Christianity's development.</p>",
"21": "<p>'The Lord's hand was with them' (<em>cheir Kyriou ēn met' autōn</em>) — the idiom 'hand of the Lord' (<em>cheir Kyriou</em>) is the OT power-formula for divine intervention in history: Exod 9:3; Judg 2:15; 1 Sam 5:6, 11; 2 Sam 24:14; 1 Kgs 18:46; 2 Kgs 3:15; Isa 66:14; Ezek 1:3. Luke's application of this OT divine-power formula to the Antioch mission validates it as genuine divine action: the unnamed missionaries from Cyprus and Cyrene are as much instruments of the divine 'hand' as Moses was at the Exodus.</p>",
"22": "<p>'The church at Jerusalem sent Barnabas to Antioch' — Barnabas's appointment as Jerusalem's investigative representative to the Antioch mission reflects the Jerusalem church's continuing sense of responsibility for the wider mission and its authority to validate or correct significant developments. Barnabas (4:36 — a Levite from Cyprus) is ideally suited: as a Cypriot himself, he shares the cultural background of the Cyprus-origin missionaries. His appointment over a Jerusalem-born Jewish Christian reflects either his reputation for cross-cultural mediation or Luke's awareness that his Cypriot origin made him the natural choice for evaluating a Cyprus-initiated mission.</p>",
"23": "<p>'He saw what the grace of God had done' (<em>idōn tēn charin tēn tou theou</em>) — the phrase identifies divine grace as visually observable: Barnabas sees something and identifies it as the grace of God. What he sees is presumably the community life, the transformed behavior, and the mixed-ethnicity fellowship of the Antioch believers. 'He was glad' (<em>echarē</em>) — his reaction is joy, not suspicion or correction. Unlike some circumcision-party critics, Barnabas accepts the evidence of grace in a Gentile-inclusive community. His encouragement to 'remain true to the Lord with all their hearts' is pastoral consolidation, not theological adjudication.</p>",
"24": "<p>'A good man, full of the Holy Spirit and faith' — Luke's character-summary of Barnabas echoes his summaries of other key figures: Stephen (6:5, 8 — full of faith and the Holy Spirit, full of grace and power), the Seven (6:3 — full of the Spirit and wisdom). The combination of 'good man' (<em>anēr agathos</em>) with pneumatological fullness and faith is Luke's profile of an effective missionary leader. 'A great number of people were brought to the Lord' (<em>prosetethe ochlos hikanos tō Kyriō</em>) — <em>prosetethe</em> (was added, passive — God does the adding) follows the Pentecost pattern (2:41, 47 — 'the Lord added to their number daily').</p>",
"25": "<p>'Then Barnabas went to Tarsus to look for Saul' (<em>anazētein Saulon</em> — to search up/out Saul) — Tarsus was Paul's home city (Acts 9:11; 21:39; 22:3), the capital of Cilicia on the Aegean-Mediterranean coast of modern Turkey, and a significant intellectual center (Strabo described it as surpassing Athens and Alexandria in philosophical culture). After his Damascus experience (9:1-25) and Jerusalem visit (9:26-29), Paul had been sent to Tarsus (9:30 — 'the believers sent him to Tarsus'). The period between Paul's Tarsus departure and Barnabas's recruitment — perhaps 5-7 years — is largely unaccounted for in Acts (cf. Gal 1:21-2:1 — Paul in Syria and Cilicia).</p>",
"26": "<p>'The disciples were first called Christians (<em>Christianous</em>) at Antioch' — the name <em>Christianos</em> (one belonging to Christus/Christ) is a Latin-style formation using the -<em>ianus</em> suffix that designated adherents or partisans of a leader (Pompeianus = Pompey's man; Herodianus = Herod's man). The name was apparently given by outsiders — Antioch's Greek-speaking Gentile population would have recognized the movement's focus on 'the Christ' and designated its members accordingly. Luke's note that the name originated in Antioch (not Jerusalem) places the first distinctively Gentile-identified label for the movement in the city where Gentile Christianity first took organizational form.</p>",
"27": "<p>'Some prophets came down from Jerusalem to Antioch' — the prophets (<em>prophētai</em>) who traveled from Jerusalem to Antioch represent a mobile charismatic ministry distinct from the settled leadership of local churches (elders, teachers). Acts mentions prophets repeatedly: Agabus (11:28; 21:10), Philip's four daughters (21:9), Barnabas, Simeon Niger, Lucius, Manaen, and Saul (13:1). The Didache (11:3-12) provides procedures for evaluating itinerant prophets, suggesting this was a significant and sometimes problematic feature of early church life. The Jerusalem-to-Antioch direction of prophetic travel reflects Jerusalem's continued role as the movement's spiritual capital.</p>",
"28": "<p>Agabus's famine prophecy (<em>esēmanen dia tou pneumatos limon megan mellein eseshai eph' holēn tēn oikoumenēn</em> — signified through the Spirit that a great famine was about to come upon the whole inhabited world) — the word <em>sēmainō</em> (to signify, indicate) is John's vocabulary for prophetic sign-speech (John 12:33; 18:32; 21:19; Rev 1:1). The famine 'over the entire Roman world' (<em>oikoumenē</em> — the inhabited world, standard Roman geographical designation for the empire) was not a single global event but a series of regional famines under Claudius (41-54 CE). Josephus describes a severe famine in Palestine under procurators Fadus and Alexander (ca. 46-48 CE; <em>Ant.</em> 20.5.2). Luke's editorial note ('this happened during the reign of Claudius') is one of Acts' explicit historical synchronizations.</p>",
"29": "<p>'The disciples, as each one was able, decided to provide help for the brothers and sisters living in Judea' (<em>kathōs ēuporeitō tis</em> — according as each one was prospering/had the means) — the collection's ability-proportioned structure ('as each one was able') corresponds to Paul's later instructions about the Corinthian collection (1 Cor 16:2 — 'each of you is to put something aside and store it up, as he may prosper'; 2 Cor 8:12 — 'it is acceptable according to what a person has'). The Antioch relief collection is the first inter-church financial solidarity action in Acts — Gentile-majority Antioch supporting the Jewish-majority Jerusalem community, reversing the expected direction of cultural dependency.</p>",
"30": "<p>'Sending their gift to the elders by Barnabas and Saul' — the 'elders' (<em>presbyterous</em>) receiving the relief collection represent the leadership structure that has emerged in Jerusalem alongside (or replacing) the apostolic oversight of the early chapters. The term <em>presbyteros</em> (elder) derives from the Jewish synagogue's elder-board (<em>zqenim</em>) and appears here for the first time in Acts as a Jerusalem leadership designation. Paul and Barnabas's joint delivery of the relief gift marks the first explicit collaboration of these two figures — the partnership that will characterize the first missionary journey (Acts 13-14).</p>"
}
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'acts')
    merge_comm(existing, ACTS_CH10_11)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'acts', existing)
    for ck in ['10', '11']:
        count = len(existing.get(ck, {}))
        print(f'Acts {ck}: {count} verses.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
